---
import StarlightPage from '@astrojs/starlight/components/StarlightPage.astro';
import Hero from '../components/home/Hero.astro';
import { YouTube } from 'astro-embed';

const content = {
  title: 'MapConductor',
  description: 'A unified map SDK for mobile app developers',
  subtitle: 'A unified map SDK\nfor mobile app developers',
  heroMessage: `Let's make\nmap apps\neasier to build`,
  paragraphs: [
    '',
    '',
  ],
  paragraphs2Title: 'Even pros don\'t know everything...',
  paragraphs2: [
    'MapConductor is an open-source SDK that lets you work with multiple map SDKs through a unified API. You don\'t need to relearn the API for each map provider, and you can focus on what you really want to do: displaying data on the map.',
    'The project is aimed at general-purpose location-based applications and is built to be approachable even for developers who are new to Android or iOS.',
  ],
  buttons: {
    getStarted: 'Overview',
    developers: 'For Developers'
  }
};
---

<StarlightPage frontmatter={{ title: content.title, description: content.description }}>
  <Hero title={content.title} subtitle={content.subtitle} heroMessage={content.heroMessage} />

  <div class="sl-markdown-content home-summary">
    <p>MapConductor absorbs the differences between numerous map SDKs and eliminates development complexity.
      You can focus on your business logic—how you want to display data on the map—without worrying about the detailed implementation methods of each map SDK's API.
      That's right, you can handle any supported map SDK the same way. Like an orchestra conductor handling multiple map SDKs. That's the world MapConductor aims to create.</p>
  </div>

  <div style="display: flex; gap: 1rem; margin-top: 2rem; flex-wrap: wrap;">
    <a class="sl-link-button" href="/intro" style="padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem; background: var(--sl-color-accent); color: white; text-decoration: none; border-radius: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600;">
      {content.buttons.getStarted}
    </a>
    <a class="sl-link-button" href="https://docs-android.mapconductor.com/" style="padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem; background: transparent; color: var(--sl-color-accent); text-decoration: none; border-radius: 0.5rem; border: 2px solid var(--sl-color-accent); font-weight: 600;">
      {content.buttons.developers}
    </a>
  </div>

  <h2>Promotional Video</h2>
  <YouTube id="https://youtu.be/Sh2GAsM7Qe8"
  title="MapConductor Introduction" />


  <div class="sl-markdown-content home-summary">
    <h2>Key Features</h2>
    <ul dir="auto">
      <li>
        <p dir="auto"><strong>Multi-SDK Support:</strong></p>
        <ul dir="auto">
          <li>With a single codebase, you can operate multiple major map SDKs including Google Maps, Mapbox, HERE, and ArcGIS.</li>
          <li>We aim to support over 50 SDKs in the future.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p dir="auto"><strong>Common API:</strong></p>
        <ul dir="auto">
          <li>Just use the unified methods provided by MapConductor to display, manipulate, and plot data on maps.</li>
          <li>No more need to learn the detailed conventions of each SDK.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p dir="auto"><strong>(Android) Jetpack Compose Support:</strong></p>
        <ul dir="auto">
          <li>The Android SDK is designed to be used with Jetpack Compose.</li>
          <li>You don't need to write code in XML Layout just for the map part.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p dir="auto"><strong>Freedom from Vendor Lock-in:</strong></p>
        <ul dir="auto">
          <li>You can freely switch backend map services with minimal code changes according to your project requirements.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p dir="auto"><strong>High Performance:</strong></p>
        <ul dir="auto">
          <li>Algorithms are implemented by default to smoothly handle thousands of markers</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <YouTube id="https://youtu.be/uGjpXKX0a4w"  title="Android Demonstration" />
  
  <h3>Related:</h3>
  <a href="https://orynth.dev/projects/mapconductor" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
    <img src="https://orynth.dev/api/badge/mapconductor?theme=light&style=default" alt="Featured on Orynth" width="260" height="80" />
  </a>
</StarlightPage>
